[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 52.4% of the global newly reported cases and 53.3% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 8.7 million cases. The USA reported 51.8% of cases (61 498), Brazil 20.7% (24 578), Colombia 6.9% (8181), Mexico 4.6% (5480), Peru 4.1% (4913), Argentina 3.5% (4205), and Chile 1.8% (2133).

- The European region reported 11.6% of the global newly reported cases and 8.9% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Spain reported 24.2% (6361) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Russia 20.5% (5395), France 8.6% (2254), Kazakhstan 5.8% (1526), Romania 4.2% (1104), Israel 3.9% (1037), Ukraine 3.5% (919), Turkey 3.5% (919), Uzbekistan 2.6% (686), the UK 2.6% (685), Kyrgyzstan 2.1% (548), and Germany 2.4% (633). Note that France and Spain did not report over the weekend so today's (28 Jul 2020) may reflect catch-up reporting.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5.5% of the global newly reported cases and 10.6% of global newly reported fatalities. Iraq reported 20.6% (2553), of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran 19.7% (2434), Saudi Arabia 16.1% (1993), Oman 8.5% (1053), Pakistan 7.6% (936), Morocco 4.9% (609), Kuwait 4.9% (606), and Egypt 3.4% (420). Pakistan is decreasing its daily case count steadily during the month of July 2020 (on 1 Jul 2020, Pakistan reported 4133 newly confirmed cases), while at the same time cases are increasing in Iraq, Oman and Morocco. This region remains highly active, with multiple countries still in a surge mode.

- The African region reported 5.8% of the global newly reported cases and 8.6% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 53.8% (7097) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Kenya 10.1% (1332), Ghana 9.0% (1187), Nigeria 4.9% (648), Algeria 4.7 (616), Ethiopia 4.4% (579), and Madagascar 3.0% (395). Since the beginning of July 2020, South Africa has reported daily new case counts of greater than 10 000, 18 of the 28 days, today's (28 Jul 2020) report is a major reduction from yesterday's 11 233 (27 Jul 2020).

- The Western Pacific region reported 1.7% of the global newly reported cases and 0.63% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 41.4% (1592) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 25.3% (972), Australia 13.8% (532), Singapore 12.2% (469), China 5.6% (217), and South Korea 0.73% (28).

- The South East Asia region reported 23.0% of the global newly reported cases and 18.1% of global deaths. India reported 91.3% (47 703) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 5.3% (2772) and Indonesia 2.9% (1525). India continues to be the driving force of the dominance of this region.

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific region representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 28 Jul 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. - Mod.MPP]

